The Speaking Vent is a Western Fold vent feature in the Cinderteeth Mountains known for pulsed gas emissions that produce audible resonance patterns.
Located in the volcanic terrain of the Western Fold — the same zone that housed the Spirebound Conclave's primary sanctum before the collapse — the vent emits through a narrow basalt fissure approximately two meters wide and indeterminate depth.
The emissions are not continuous but pulsed at irregular intervals, producing pressure waves that the surrounding rock amplifies into audible low-frequency tones.
Ventspeaker practice — an older interpretive tradition practiced by communities living on the Cinderteeth's lower slopes — held that the vent's pulse patterns constituted patterned warnings about seismic activity, eruption timing, and weather.
The Conclave's Ember Canon faction documented the vent extensively, treating it as a heat-signature data source rather than a voice.
After the Conclave's collapse, the vent's interpretive community contracted severely; few practitioners of formal Ventspeaker discipline remain.
Rangers operating from Kiess staging areas who travel into the Cinderteeth include the Speaking Vent's current activity status in their reports as a seismic indicator.
The vent's pulse timing has been observed to change in the days preceding significant eruption events, lending retrospective credibility to the Ventspeaker interpretive tradition.
Modern assessors treat the vent as a natural geological feature with useful predictive properties rather than as a communicating entity.
The Conclave's sealed Ember Canon records from Zone C of the sanctum include the most complete emissions log of the Speaking Vent in existence — inaccessible until those records are recovered.
The vent's sound is described by those who have heard it as bone-deep rather than ear-audible, felt through the feet and chest before it is heard.

